+# Relayfile post-auth mount DX for sandboxes
+
+## Status
+
+Proposed
+
+## Summary
+
+Cloud should expose a post-auth, workspace-attach flow that lets a sandbox mount an already-authorized Relayfile workspace with one call.
+
+Auth and provider login happen ahead of time in the product UI or backend. Inside the sandbox, the caller should not need to manually:
+
+- join a workspace
+- derive mount env vars
+- spawn `relayfile mount`
+- reason about token refresh
+
+Instead, the product should provide a single mount-oriented contract that attaches an existing workspace into a sandbox-local directory.
+
+## Problem
+
+Today the underlying pieces exist, but the DX boundary is too low-level for Daytona, E2B, and similar sandbox products.
+
+The current shape leaks internal seams:
+
+1. cloud auth/session
+2. workspace provisioning or join
+3. relayfile token minting
+4. mount env derivation
+5. local daemon launch and lifecycle
+
+That is fine for primitives, but awkward for product integration. Sandbox callers do not want to assemble a Relayfile mount from parts. They want: "attach this workspace into this directory".
+
+## Goals
+
+- Keep user login separate from sandbox mount
+- Support an already-existing cloud session or service token
+- Support an already-existing workspace id
+- Hide relayfile token minting and mount env shaping behind a single cloud contract
+- Hide daemon launch details behind a single SDK helper or launcher contract
+- Work well for Daytona, E2B, local laptop agents, and remote worker sandboxes
+- Preserve access control and workspace scoping already enforced by cloud
+
+## Non-goals
+
+- Replacing existing low-level Relayfile SDK primitives
+- Requiring FUSE in sandboxes
+- Running the Relayfile API server inside the sandbox
+- Solving provider connect UX inside the sandbox
+- Defining the full mount supervisor implementation in this doc
+
+## Product stance
+
+Auth should remain separate.
+
+The expected product flow is:
+
+1. user signs in to Cloud in app/web
+2. user selects or creates a workspace
+3. user connects providers in app/web
+4. Cloud or backend launches a sandbox
+5. sandbox receives a narrow, post-auth mount contract for that workspace
+6. sandbox attaches Relayfile locally and hands the local dir to the agent runtime
+
+This is a better boundary than bundling login into a quickstart helper.
+
+## Proposed user-facing API
+
+Two levels are recommended.
+
+### 1. Stable primitive: mount an existing workspace
+
+```ts
+const relayfile = new RelayfileSetup({
+  accessToken: cloudToken,
+});
+
+const mount = await relayfile.mountWorkspace({
+  workspaceId: "ws_123",
+  localDir: "/workspace/relayfile",
+});
+
+console.log(mount.localDir);
+```
+
+Behavior:
+
+- validates cloud access to `workspaceId`
+- obtains a short-lived Relayfile workspace token
+- derives mount env internally
+- starts the local mount process
+- waits until the mount is ready for filesystem use
+- returns a handle
+
+### 2. Optional convenience: ensure + mount
+
+```ts
+const mount = await relayfile.ensureMountedWorkspace({
+  workspace: "customer-support-room",
+  provider: "slack",
+  localDir: "/workspace/relayfile",
+});
+```
+
+Behavior:
+
+- resolves or creates the requested workspace
+- optionally verifies the requested provider is already connected
+- mounts it locally
+
+This is optional. The core product need is `mountWorkspace(...)`.
+
+## Proposed returned handle
+
+```ts
+type MountedWorkspaceHandle = {
+  workspaceId: string;
+  localDir: string;
+  remotePath: string;
+  mode: "poll" | "stream";
+  ready: boolean;
+  stop(): Promise<void>;
+  status(): Promise<{
+    ready: boolean;
+    pid?: number;
+    lastHeartbeatAt?: string;
+    mode: "poll" | "stream";
+  }>;
+  env(): Record<string, string>;
+};
+```
+
+Notes:
+
+- `env()` is exposed for debugging and advanced callers, not as the main path
+- `stop()` should terminate the child mount process or invoke the mount stop contract when backgrounded
+- `status()` should be stable enough for sandbox supervision and diagnostics
+
+## Proposed Cloud contract
+
+Cloud should own a first-class post-auth mount session endpoint.
+
+### Endpoint
+
+`POST /api/v1/workspaces/:workspaceId/relayfile/mount-session`
+
+### Request
+
+```json
+{
+  "localDir": "/workspace/relayfile",
+  "remotePath": "/",
+  "mode": "poll"
+}
+```
+
+### Response
+
+```json
+{
+  "workspaceId": "ws_123",
+  "relayfileBaseUrl": "https://relayfile.example.com",
+  "relayfileToken": "<short-lived-workspace-token>",
+  "remotePath": "/",
+  "localDir": "/workspace/relayfile",
+  "mode": "poll",
+  "expiresAt": "2026-05-09T08:30:00.000Z"
+}
+```
+
+### Semantics
+
+- caller must already be authenticated to Cloud
+- caller must have access to the workspace
+- returned token must be scoped to that workspace only
+- token should be short-lived
+- response is mount-oriented, not a generic workspace join blob
+- Cloud may mint this using existing Relayfile token machinery internally
+
+## Proposed SDK layering
+
+### Cloud SDK / product SDK
+
+Cloud-facing SDK should offer:
+
+```ts
+mountWorkspace(input: {
+  workspaceId: string;
+  localDir: string;
+  remotePath?: string;
+  mode?: "poll" | "stream";
+  background?: boolean;
+}): Promise<MountedWorkspaceHandle>
+```
+
+Internally it would:
+
+1. call the mount-session endpoint
+2. translate response into env vars
+3. launch `relayfile mount`
+4. wait for readiness
+5. return the handle
+
+### Relayfile SDK
+
+Existing low-level methods remain valid:
+
+- `mountEnv()`
+- workspace join/setup primitives
+- direct client usage without local mount
+
+But they become implementation details for most sandbox consumers.
+
+## Why this is better DX
+
+It matches the real mental model.
+
+The sandbox integrator is not asking:
+
+- how do I derive `RELAYFILE_TOKEN`?
+- how do I refresh workspace join state?
+- how do I construct mount env?
+
+They are asking:
+
+- how do I attach this workspace here?
+
+That should be one method and one server contract.
+
+## Sandbox examples
+
+### Daytona
+
+```ts
+const mount = await relayfile.mountWorkspace({
+  workspaceId,
+  localDir: "/workspace/relayfile",
+});
+
+agentRoot = mount.localDir;
+```
+
+### E2B
+
+```ts
+const mount = await relayfile.mountWorkspace({
+  workspaceId,
+  localDir: "/home/user/relayfile",
+  mode: "poll",
+});
+```
+
+### Local dev agent
+
+```ts
+const mount = await relayfile.mountWorkspace({
+  workspaceId,
+  localDir: "./.relayfile",
+});
+```
+
+## Lifecycle expectations
+
+Default expectations:
+
+- foreground mode when the sandbox runtime already supervises long-lived processes
+- optional background mode for bootstrap scripts
+- mount readiness must not resolve early before the directory is usable
+- token refresh should be automatic as long as the parent cloud session remains valid
+
+If automatic refresh is not supported in v1, the contract must say so explicitly and return a short-lived mount session intended only for short sandbox runs.
+
+## Security properties
+
+- no upstream provider secrets in sandbox env
+- no global Relayfile admin secret in sandbox env
+- only a workspace-scoped Relayfile token enters the sandbox
+- cloud access check happens before issuing mount session
+- mount session should be auditable by workspace and caller
+
+## Recommended implementation slices
+
+### Slice 1, spec + endpoint
+
+- add `POST /api/v1/workspaces/:workspaceId/relayfile/mount-session`
+- mint workspace-scoped Relayfile token
+- return mount-session payload
+- cover auth and workspace access behavior
+
+### Slice 2, SDK helper
+
+- add `mountWorkspace(...)` in the cloud-facing SDK or helper package
+- call mount-session endpoint
+- launch `relayfile mount`
+- wait for readiness
+- return handle
+
+### Slice 3, product integration
+
+- wire Daytona or workflow sandbox launch path to call `mountWorkspace(...)`
+- pass resulting `localDir` to agent runtime
+
+## Open questions
+
+1. Should Cloud return only the mount session payload, or should it also support a managed launcher endpoint for non-Node runtimes?
+2. Do we want `mountWorkspace(...)` on `RelayfileSetup`, or a Cloud-specific helper to avoid conflating direct Relayfile SDK concerns with hosted product orchestration?
+3. What is the v1 readiness signal, successful process spawn, status probe, or filesystem sentinel?
+4. Do we need explicit reconnect semantics for long-lived sandboxes that outlive the original cloud auth session?
+
+## Recommendation
+
+Adopt the post-auth mount-session contract and expose `mountWorkspace(...)` as the primary sandbox integration API.
+
+That gives us the right abstraction boundary:
+
+- auth is handled ahead of time
+- workspace authorization remains in Cloud
+- sandbox attachment becomes one call
+- low-level Relayfile pieces remain available without becoming the default product DX
